{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{Infobox royalty |name = George Tupou V |image = George Tupou V Coronation.jpg |succession = [[List of monarchs of Tonga|King of Tonga]] |reign = 11 September 2006 – 18 March 2012 |coronation = 1 August 2008 |predecessor = [[Tāufaʻāhau Tupou IV]] |successor = [[Tupou VI]] |reg-type = {{nowrap|[[Prime Minister of Tonga|Prime Ministers]]}} |regent = {{List collapsed|title=''See list''|1=[[Feleti Sevele]]
[[Sialeʻataongo Tuʻivakanō]]}} |issue = [['Ilima Lei Tohi]] (Illegitimate) |full name = Siaosi Tāufaʻāhau Manumataongo Tukuʻaho |house = House of Tupou |father = [[Tāufaʻāhau Tupou IV]] |mother = [[Halaevalu Mataʻaho ʻAhomeʻe]] |birth_date = {{birth date|1948|5|4|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Tongatapu]], [[Tonga]] |death_date = {{death date and age|2012|3|18|1948|5|4|df=y}} |death_place = [[Pok Fu Lam]], [[Hong Kong]] }} '''George Tupou V''' ([[Tongan language|Tongan]]: '''Siaosi Tupou V''', full name: '''Siaosi Tāufa{{okina}}āhau Manumataongo Tuku{{okina}}aho Tupou V'''; 4 May 1948{{ndash}} 18 March 2012) was the [[List of Tongan Monarchs|King]] of [[Tonga]][http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/tongan-monarch-dies-at-63/story-e6frg6so-1226303362395 "Tongan monarch dies at 63"] ''The Australian'' following the death of his father, [[Tāufaʻāhau Tupou IV]] in 2006, until his own death six years later. ==Biography== Tupou V was born on 4 May 1948. He was the eldest son of King [[Taufa'ahau Tupou IV|Tāufa{{okina}}āhau Tupou IV]] (1918–2006) and Queen [[Halaevalu Mataʻaho ʻAhomeʻe|Halaevalu Mata{{okina}}aho {{okina}}Ahome{{okina}}e]] (born 1926). He was appointed [[Crown Prince]] on 4 May 1966. In that role, he was better known by one of his traditional chiefly titles, '''Tupouto{{okina}}a'''. Tupou V attended [[King's School (Auckland)|King's School]] and [[King's College, Auckland|King's College]], both in [[Auckland]]. This was followed by periods at [[The Leys School]] in Cambridge, and another school in Switzerland.[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article4419058.ece Crowning glory or a costly folly? George Tupou V's coronation divides Tonga] The Sunday Times, 29 July 2008 He also studied at [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]] and the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] in England. ===Issue=== Though unmarried, Tupou V had a daughter born out of wedlock, [['Ilima Lei Tohi|'Ilima Lei Fifita Tohi]] (born 1974). She married police officer [[Tulutulumafua i'Olotele Kalaniuvalu]] in 1997, and has three children. According to the [[Constitution of Tonga]], {{okina}}Ilima is ineligible to accede to the throne as only children born of a royal marriage may [[Line of succession to the Tongan throne|inherit the royal succession]].{{cite news |date=17 September 2006 |author=Jane Phare |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/story.cfm?c_id=2&ObjectID=10401690 |title=The madness of King George of Tonga |work=The New Zealand Herald |accessdate=21 October 2006}} ==Crown Prince== As Crown Prince, Tupouto{{okina}}a held great influence in Tongan politics, and was [[Minister for Foreign Affairs]] from 1979 to 1998. He had substantial business interests in Tonga and abroad, and was co-chairman of the [[Shoreline Group]]/[[Tonfön]]. As king, his first proclamation was that he would dispose of all his business assets as soon as reasonably possible, and in accordance with the law. Tonfön had since been sold, but the King was unable during his lifetime to rid himself of the remainder of the Shoreline Group after the [[2006 Nuku'alofa riots]] scared potential buyers from making a deal.{{or|date=March 2012}} ==Reign== {{Infobox Monarch styles |royal name = King George Tupou V of Tonga |image = [[File:Coat of arms of Tonga.svg|70px]] |dipstyle = His Majesty
''ko ʻene ʻafio'' |offstyle = Your Majesty
''ko hoʻo ʻafio'' |altstyle = Sir}} The King was recognised as a descendant of the sky god [[Tangaloa]].[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/royalty-obituaries/9151791/His-Majesty-King-George-Tupou-V-of-Tonga.html His Majesty King George Tupou V of Tonga – Telegraph] He was sworn in as King Tupou V on 11 September 2006,[http://www.pmo.gov.to/artman/publish/article_170.shtml Tongan Government Gazette Publication 20] and [http://www.pmo.gov.to/artman/publish/article_172.shtml Gazette Publication 19] It might be argued that he became King on his swearing in (11 Sept, midday), or on the death of his father the night before. However, although the death of his father occurred on 10 September at 23:34 in New Zealand, Siaosi was in Tonga, where the time was 0:34, 11 September. which also made him, from a traditional viewpoint, the 23rd [[Tu'i Kanokupolu|Tu{{okina}}i Kanokupolu]] (the overlords of [[Tongatapu]]). ===Enthronement=== The ceremonial aspects of Tupou V's accession took place in July and August 2008. These were initially to be held in 2007 after the six-month [[official mourning]] period for his father (as required of close relatives) and his own birthday. This was deferred after the [[2006 Tonga riots]] as he decided to focus instead on reconstruction of the damaged capital.[http://www.matangitonga.to/article/tonganews/royalty/coronation301106.shtml user account | Matangi Tonga Online] During the week of celebrations, two key ceremonies took place to mark Tupou V's coronation. On 30 July 2008, a ''Taumafa Kava'' ceremony (Royal Kava Ring) was held on Mala{{okina}}e Pangai, the open space to the east of the Royal Palace. During the ceremony, Tupou V sat on a pile of handwoven pandanus mats in an open pavilion facing the sea, while more than 200 Tongan nobles and chiefs dressed in woven skirts and sea shells circled him. He wore the traditional Tongan ''[[ta'ovala]]'' (woven mat skirt) and a garland of flowers. During this ceremony, Tupou V was formally recognised as the ''Tu{{okina}}i Kanokupolu'', and the rightful descendent of King George Tupou I who united Tonga in the 19th century. The ceremony involved having ''[[kava]]'', hundreds of baskets of food, and seventy cooked pigs presented to the King and the assembly of chiefs and nobles,{{cite news|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/page/411366/1960158|title=King of Tonga crowned|date= 1 August 2008|publisher=TV New Zealand|accessdate=1 August 2008}} Later that night, schoolchildren held 30,000 torches to proclaim the coronation in what is known as a ''tupakapakanava''. The traditional torch spectacle was held that time at a spot overlooking the Pacific and is an ancient honour accorded to the monarch and the royal family only.{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/travel/2008/jul/30/tonga?gusrc=rss&feed=networkfront|title=Gutted pigs and narcotic drinks welcome new king of Tonga|first=Barbara McMahon |date= 30 July 2008|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=1 August 2008 }} A second, European-style [[coronation]] ceremony took place on 1 August 2008 in the Centennial Chapel, Nuku’alofa.{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article4440717.ece|title=Lavish coronation ceremony for new King of Tonga|date= 1 August 2008|work=The Times |location=London |accessdate=1 August 2008 | first=Sophie | last=Tedmanson}} [[Diocese of Polynesia|Anglican Archbishop of Polynesia]] [[Jabez Bryce]] invested George Tupou V with the Tongan regalia: the ring, sceptre and sword. In the culmination of the ceremony, Archbishop Bryce placed the Tongan Crown on the monarch's head. Royalty and nobility from around the world were in attendance.{{cite news |url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gallery/2008/jul/31/1 |title= Tonga's Coronation celebrations |newspaper=The Guardian (UK) |first = |last= |date= 1 August 2008 |accessdate= 24 March 2012}} ===Relinquishing authority=== Three days before his coronation on 1 August 2008, the King announced that he would relinquish most of his power and be guided by his [[Prime Minister of Tonga|Prime Minister]]'s recommendations on most matters.[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7530209.stm "Tonga's king to cede key powers"], BBC, 29 July 2008 The Prime Minister would also be in charge of day-to-day affairs.{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2008/jul/29/1|title=Tongan king promises 'more democracy' for Pacific island|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=29 July 2008|date=29 July 2008 | first=Barbara | last=McMahon}} Tupou V would still have the powers to appoint judges and [[commutation of sentence|commute prison sentences]].{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/07/29/tonga.king/|title=Tongan king to give up absolute rule|publisher=CNN|accessdate=29 July 2008|date=29 July 2008}} The King also sold off lucrative business interests as part of the announcement.{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/category/story.cfm?c_id=72&objectid=10524265|title=Feudal monarch agrees to give up much of his power|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=29 July 2008|date=29 July 2008|deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=December 2011|bot=RjwilmsiBot}} In addition, the King announced that there would be parliamentary reform and elections in 2010.{{cite news|url=http://fijidailypost.com/feature.php?date=20080728&index=575|title=His Majesty King George Tupou V- A Monarch for a time of change |work=Fiji Daily Post|accessdate=28 July 2008|date=29 July 2008}} Fielakepa, the spokesman for the royal palace, said, "The Sovereign of the only [[Polynesia]]n kingdom ... is voluntarily surrendering his powers to meet the democratic aspirations of many of his people ... [The people] favour a more representative, elected [[Legislative Assembly of Tonga|Parliament]]. The king agrees with them." [http://www.youtube.com/watch?NR=1&feature=fvwp&v=LFQW2Xq6aS8 A documentary] dated June 2004 from Australian journalist Gillian Bradford identifies some of the challenges facing Tongan society, but also shows (contrary to what is stated in the introductory note) that King George was in favour of a gradual transition to more extensive democracy in Tonga. In the interview, the Crown Prince, as he then was, points out that free speech in Tonga was protected by the ConstitutionGillian Bradford, ABC, http://www.youtube.com/watch?NR=1&feature=fvwp&v=LFQW2Xq6aS8. In July 2010 the government published a new electoral roll and called Tonga's 101,900 citizens to add their names to the document so that they can take part in the historic vote, which was due to be held on 25 November. He would remain head of state, but lose his executive powers, including the ability to appoint the prime minister and ministers.[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/australiaandthepacific/tongafrenchpolynesia/7884094/King-of-Tonga-prepares-to-give-up-power.html King of Tonga prepares to give up power] However, it seemed certain that the Monarch would continue to appoint and administer the Judiciary of Tonga for the purposes of assuring that political independence and neutrality were retained.{{cite news|url=https://www.pmo.gov.to/privy-council-approves-establishment-of-royal-commission-of-inquiry-into-reports-that-government-has-attempted-unduly-to-influence-the-independence-of-the-judiciary.html|title=Privy Council establishes Commission of Inquiry|publisher=Government of Tonga|accessdate=12 August 2010|year=2010}}{{dead link|date=September 2011}} ==Illness and death== Six months before his death, Tupou V had surgery to remove a kidney following the discovery of a tumour.AFP [http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jYXx7DXfIG-_8So_58AyAFJ5LByw?docId=CNG.05c3b6ca0ada9e66b7fb77d3fff34bd6.841 "Tonga's reformist king dies aged 63"] ''[[Matangi Tonga]]'' reported that George Tupou V died from [[leukemia]] at 15:15 [[Hong Kong Time|HKT]] 18 March 2012 at [[Queen Mary Hospital, Hong Kong|Queen Mary Hospital]] in [[Pok Fu Lam]], Hong Kong,http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/template/apple/art_main.php?iss_id=20120319&sec_id=4104&subsec_id=12731&art_id=16168607 though governing institutions in Tonga did not immediately confirm it. His brother and Crown Prince [[Tupouto'a Lavaka]] was at the hospital when he died.[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2012/03/201231812573157504.html Tonga king dies in Hong Kong hospital – Asia-Pacific – Al Jazeera English] ===Reactions=== ====Domestic==== A statement was due following a cabinet meeting the day after his death. [[Radio Australia]] reported that Tonga's largest religious organisation, the [[Free Wesleyan Church]], said it would hold a prayer service at the [[queen mother]]'s residence in [[Nuku'alofa]].[http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jYXx7DXfIG-_8So_58AyAFJ5LByw?docId=CNG.05c3b6ca0ada9e66b7fb77d3fff34bd6.841 AFP: Tonga's reformist king dies aged 63: PM] Prime Minister [[Lord Tu'ivakano]] later made a national address calling on the people of Tonga to pray for the royal family and the country, according to ''[[Radio New Zealand]]''. ====International==== *[[Queen Elizabeth II]] sent a message of condolence saying that King Tupou was "a true statesman who served his country with distinction".http://www.royal.gov.uk/LatestNewsandDiary/Pressreleases/2012/MessageofCondolenceTheKingofTonga.aspx *[[King Harald V of Norway]] sent a message of condolence to King Tupou VI, in which he expresses sympathy for the new King, his family and the people of Tonga.http://www.kongehuset.no/c27262/nyhet/vis.html?tid=99792 *Australian Prime Minister [[Julia Gillard]] said that King Tupou's death was the loss of "a great friend" to Australia and pointed to the change he led Tonga through as the "first truly democratic elections, held in November 2010, set the country on a new course." *New Zealand Prime Minister [[John Key]] said: "He believed that the monarchy was an instrument of change and can truly be seen as the architect of evolving democracy in Tonga. This will be his enduring legacy."http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/Australia/Tonga-in-mourning-after-king-aged-63-dies/Article1-827495.aspx Maori King [[Tuheitia Paki|Tuheitia]] said: "He kura i tangihia, he maimai aroha" which means condolences to the Royal Family and the people of Tonga.http://pacific.scoop.co.nz/2012/03/kiingi-tuheitia-extends-condolences-to-tonga/ *United States President [[Barack Obama]] said that King Tupou's death was the loss of "a friend" to the United States and the loss of "a visionary leader" to the people of Tonga.{{cite press release|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2012/03/19/statement-president-passing-king-george-tupou-v-tonga|title=Statement by the President on the Passing of King George Tupou V of Tonga|last=Obama|first=Barack|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=19 March 2012|publuhser= The White House}} ===Funeral=== Following the official announcement of the passing of King George Tupou V and giving the Proclamation of the New King, Tupou VI, His Majesty's Cabinet set up a Committee for the organization of the state funeral of the late King. Lord Vaea became the Chairman of the Committee. The late King's body is scheduled to arrive on Monday, 26 March 2012. It is then to lie in state at the Royal Palace in Nuku'alofa for a day.http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=10794276 The funeral, originally announced for 28 March 2012, has been rescheduled to 27 March 2012. ====Official guests==== Selected foreign dignitaries have been invited by the Committee to attend the funeral. As of 24 March 2012, the attendance of the Governor General of Australia, Quentin Bryce, and the Governor-General of New Zealand, Jerry Mataparae, have been confirmed. Royal guests at the ceremony included [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester]] and [[Prince Hitachi]] of Japan and his wife.http://matangitonga.to/2012/03/21/king-george-tupou-vs-burial-date-be-confirmed ==Honours and awards== On 15 September 2011 he received the Grand Cross of the Order of Merit of the Hungarian Republic from [[Pál Schmitt]], the president of [[Hungary]].[http://www.origo.hu/itthon/20110915-schmitt-pal-allami-kituntetest-adott-v-george-tupou-tongai-kiralynak.html Rajong a magyarokért a Schmitt Pál által kitüntetett király] In February 2012 the King received the Knight Grand Cross of the [[Royal Order of Francis I]] from [[Prince Carlo, Duke of Castro]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} ==Ancestry== {{Unreferenced section|date=March 2012}} {{ahnentafel top|width=100%}}
